Introduction

  • one of the most popular sports in the world

  • unlike other similarly popular sports, it has evolved with new rules and formats

    • soccer has remained a 90 minute match in record history, while cricket matches can last from anywhere between 3 hours to 5 days

  • common feature of all formats is that there is a team that bats first, while the other team fields and bowls

    • in the longer versions of the game, both teams are alloted two innings each, while in shorter versions each team bats for an innings

  • innings produce an inherent asymmetry of the game because

  • weather conditions may be more conducive to batting earlier in the day

  • psychological effects of chasing targets vs being first-mover

  • this asymmetry is mitigated by having a coin toss, in which the team that wins the toss gets to choose whether they bat or field first

    • therefore winning the toss can have a profound impact on the odds of winning or losing the game that gives one team an advantage in win probability against the other team even before a single ball is bowled

  • normative question: are these asymmetries created by the toss an inherent part of the game that we all accept, or do they detract from the integrity and fairness of the game,

    • some people might say that since the toss is random, the unfairness is not objectionable, since teams eventually
    • however, some matches (such as knock-out matches in world cups) are of such consequences that their outcome ought to depend on the skill, stamina, training, decisionmaking, and coaching and leadership of captain etc rather than the outcome of a random event that occurs before a single ball is bowled, before a single ball is bowled, so the argument goes

  • In this paper, we investigate the impacts of these asymmetries on match outcomes using an original dataset of 60,000 cricket matches played over the course of the last century. This is the most comprehensive cricket match dataset to our knowledge

  • Our analysis proceeds in the following series of steps

    • is the toss random?
    • what is the effect of winning the toss on winning the game?
      • 2%
      • team strength
      • is it higher for more competitive games?
      • match types
      • how does this vary by the competing teams’ characteristics
      • stakes of the tournament
    • since the toss endows one of the captains with the choice of batting first or second, how do captains use the toss to their advantage
    • in other words, what is the effect of having the choice to bat first and choosing to do so?
      • hetergeneous effects
      • IV
      • Kappa

  • can we do this in terms of runs? this is the policy relevant quantity

reg_by_group = function(df, groupvar, fml){
  require(dplyr) ; require(purrr) ; require(broom)
  group_reg_tables = df %>%
    group_by({{groupvar}}) %>%
    group_map( ~ robustify(felm(fml, .x)) %>%
      tidy %>% mutate(group = .y[[1]]), .keep = T)
  return(group_reg_tables)
}

coefplotter = function(df, title){
  df %>%
    mutate(term2 = paste0(group, '_', term)) %>%
    ggplot(. , aes(y = group, x = estimate) ) +
      geom_point(colour = '#6495ed') +
      geom_pointrange(aes(
        xmin = estimate - 1.96 * `std.error`,
        xmax = estimate + 1.96 * `std.error`,
      ), colour = "#6495ed", alpha = 0.8) +
    labs(title = title, x = "", y = "") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = 'dotted')
}

Characterising Compliers

\[ P(D_1 > D_0) = E[D_1 - D_0] = E[D | Z = 1] - E[D | Z = 0] \]

mu = regsamp[, mean(bat_first), wintoss][, V1]
always_takers = nrow(regsamp[wintoss != 1 & bat_first == 1]) / nrow(regsamp[wintoss != 1])
never_takers =  nrow(regsamp[wintoss == 1 & bat_first == 0]) / nrow(regsamp[wintoss == 1])
compliers = mu[2] - mu[1]


shares = data.frame(subpop = c('always takers', 'never takers', 'compliers'),
           share  = c(always_takers, never_takers, compliers[1]))

\(\kappa\) weighted summary statistics

The relative likelihood that a complier has \(X = x\) is given by the ratio of the first stage for the subpopulation with \(X = x\) to the overall first stage.

Target: mean for compliers

\[ E[X | D_1 > D_0] = \frac{E[\kappa X]}{E[\kappa]} \]

where

\[ \kappa = 1 - \frac{D (1-Z)}{P(Z = 0 | X)} - \frac{(1-D) Z}{P(Z = 1 | X)} \]

  • \(\approx\) 1 for identifiable compliers
  • \(\approx\) -1 for identifiable always takers
  • \(\approx\) -1 for identifiable never takers

Covars considered:

  • underdog - lower ranked team in match
  • day-night matches
  • home team
samp2 = regsamp[!is.na(rank) & !is.na(home_country)]
samp2[, lowrank := min(rank) , by = mid]
samp2[, underdog := ifelse(rank == lowrank, 1, 0)]
samp2[, dn := 1*(day_n_night == "day/night match")]
samp2[, home := 1*home_country]
samp2 = dummy_cols(samp2, select_columns = c('time_unit', 'continent')) %>%
  clean_names()


kappa_avg = function(xn, df = samp2) {
  x = as.matrix(df[, ..xn]); y = as.matrix(df$wingame)
  d = df$bat_first; z = df$wintoss
  ϕ = glm(z ~ x, family = binomial())$fitted.values
  κ = 1 - (d * (1-z))/(1-ϕ) - ((1-d) * z)/ϕ
  mean(κ * x) / mean(κ)
}

Local Average Response Function

CEF of \(Y|X,D\) for subpopulation of compliers.

Target : \(E[Y | X, D, D_1 > D_0]\).

Estimate using Kappa weighting.

larf_fit = function(xn, df = samp2) {
  X = as.matrix(df[, ..xn]); y = as.matrix(df$wingame)
  d = df$bat_first; z = df$wintoss
  ϕ = glm(z ~ X, family = binomial())$fitted.values
  κ = 1 - (d * (1-z))/(1-ϕ) - ((1-d) * z)/ϕ
  Xw = cbind(1, X, d)
  larf <- solve(t(Xw) %*% diag(κ) %*% Xw ) %*% t(Xw) %*% diag(κ) %*% y
  return(larf)
}

cum_run_curves = function(df){
  subt = paste(unique(df$teamShortName) , collapse = ' vs ')
  df[, remaining_wickets := 11 - totalWicket]
  # max run tallies
  totruns = df[, max(totalRuns), by = 'innings']
  # figure
  f = ggplot(df, aes(over, totalRuns, colour = as.factor(innings))) +
    geom_point(aes(alpha = remaining_wickets)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = totruns[1, 2][[1]], colour = 'red', alpha = 0.5, linetype = 'dashed') +
    geom_hline(yintercept = totruns[2, 2][[1]], colour = 'blue' , alpha = 0.5, linetype = 'dashed') +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 50, alpha = 0.5, linetype = 'dotted') +
    scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
    labs(subtitle = subt, caption = 'alpha scaled by number of wickets left',
      colour = 'Innings') + scale_alpha(guide = 'none')
  return(f)
}
